@node COMMANDS "Commands"

Commands for the GUI file

bool values:
To set to true you can use 1, true, yes, t or just nothing.
To set to false you can use 0, f, false or no.
All possibilities are case insensitive.

strings:
You have to use quote characters (") when your string contains spaces.

The commands are case sensitive. Parameters in square brackets are
optional.

@{u}title <string> @{uu}
Sets the window title.
Example:
title "Indent parameters"

@{u}page [name] @{uu}
You can spread your parameter gadgets over several pages. This command
creates a new page. ConfGui creates a page if your first gadget isn't
a page gadget.
Example:
page "Page 2"

@{u}bool <name> [default] @{uu}
Creates a checkbox gadget.
Example:
bool --honour-newlines TRUE

@{u}integer <name> [default] [minimum] [maximum] @{uu}
Creates an integer gadget.
Example:
integer --number 4
integer --number 4 -5 6

@{u}string <name> [default] @{uu}
Creates a string input gadget
string --name
Example:
string --name "Amiga"

@{u}file <name> [default] @{uu}
file --filename
Example:
file --filename "work:"

@{u}enum <name> <default index> [name1] [name2] ...  @{uu}
Creates a chooser gadget. Index starts from 0.
Example:
enum -directions 2 left right up down

@{u}hint <string> @{uu}
This adds a hint string to the previous defined gadget. The string is shown
as "bubble help" when you move the mouse over the gadget. You can
repeat the hint command to create multiline help.
Example:
hint "Do not prefer to break long lines"
hint "at the position of newlines in the input."

@{u}commends @{uu}
If the first non-whitespace character of a line isn't alphanumeric or
'-' or '_' it is treated as commend and ignored.

@endnode
@node INSTALL "Installation"

The binary 'confgui' is in bin/vbcc-classic. Copy it somewhere to your search path.

@endnode

@node PARAMETERS "Parameters"

This commands influence how the configuration file is read or
written:

@{u}writetrue <string> @{uu}
The string is written, when the value of a bool parameter is true.
The string must not contain spaces or quote (") characters.
If you don't specify this command then the configuration parameter
is written without a value.
Example:
writetrue TRUE

@{u}writefalse <string> @{uu}
The string is written, when the value of a bool parameter is false.
The string must not contain spaces or quote (") characters.
If you don't specify this parameter then nothing is written for the
configuration parameter.
Writefalse effects reading configuration files, too:
If a parameter doesn't exist in the configuration file and writefalse
isn't specified then the default parameter of the gadget is overwritten
with 'false'.
Example:
writefalse no

@{u}separator <char> @{uu}
The separator divides the parameter and the value. When reading the
configuration file the separator is treated optional. When writing the
separator is put between the parameter and the value. (You can
suppress the separator with the 'singlehyphen' command.)
Example:
separator =

@{u}singlehyphen <bool> @{uu}
Suppresses the separator when the parameter starts with a single '-'.

@{u}onevalue <bool> @{uu}
When true the content after the separator is treated as one single value.
Quote characters (") are read as they are.
When set to false then the string after the separator is divided into
one or more strings. Space characters are the delimiter. You
must use quote characters if your value should contain spaces.
(Example: "the value")
If the value should contain quote charaters you have to prefix it
with a back slash (\\").

@{u}noemptystrings <bool> @{uu}
Doesn't write string values when they are empty.
Noemptystrings effects reading configuration files, too:
If a parameter doesn't exist in the configuration file and noemptystrings
is specified then the default parameter of the gadget is overwritten
with an empty string.
@endnode

@node GETOPT "getopt"

Many applications from the Linux world use 'getopt' to read the
command line parameters. Some let you write the parameters into a file
in a getopt-like style.

Recommended gui file commands:
singlehyphen true
separator =

Limitations:
You can not accumulate parameters like -abc. You have to write this as
-a
-b
-c

Short parameters with a value must be separated by a space
-o file.dat instead of -ofile.dat

@endnode

@node TIDY "HTML-Tidy"

Recommended gui file commands for HTML-Tidy:
separator :
writetrue true
writefalse false
onevalue true

Limitation: You cannot spread a value over several lines.

@endnode

@node GUIFILES "Gui files"

ConfGui comes with 2 example gui files:

indent.dlg for GNU/Indent
@{"Screenshot" link "confgui-indent.png/main"}

tidy.dlg for HTML-Tidy
@{"Screenshot" link "confgui-tidy.png/main"}
Example call with GoldED/Webworld:
confgui g=guifiles/tidy.dlg c=golded:add-ons/webworld/tidy/config/tidy2.config

@endnode

@node PROBLEMS "Known problems"

ConfGui strips all comments from the configuration file.

Some Applications use diffent formats for command line and
configuration file. Example: GNU/indent doesn't like separators
between parameter and value in configuration files.

If you write your gui file with long parameters and an existing
configuration file has short parameters: bad luck.

@endnode

@node COMPILING "Compiling"

ConfGui was compiled with vbcc 0.8h with the options:
-lvcs -sc -sd -lamigas -cpp-comments
The program fails when compiled with optimizer level >=2.

@endnode

